body:
I'm using Verilator 5.018 2023-10-30 rev UNKNOWN.REV in Ubuntu 22.04

Something wrong is happening when I refer to a parameter in an interface in a for-loop of a generate statement:

Interface with a parameter:

intf.sv
~~~~
interface intf
#(
 parameter WIDTH = 10
) (
  input clk
);

endinterface
~~~~

Top level module:

top.sv:
~~~~
module top ( input clk );

intf #(.WIDTH(10)) g (.clk (clk));

t i_t ( .g (g) );

endmodule
~~~~

Sub module where we instantiate a new interface:

t.sv
~~~~
module t  ( intf g );

intf #(.WIDTH(20)) h (.clk(g.clk));   // Override WIDTH

u i_u  ( .g (h) );  // Pass in new interface

endmodule
~~~~

Module with generate:

u.sv:
~~~~
module u ( intf g );

logic [3:0] array[g.WIDTH:0];   <---- g.WIDTH is 20 here, correct.

genvar i;
generate
  for (i = 0; i != g.WIDTH; i = i + 1)   <--- g.WIDTH is 10 here??? This is wrong.
  //for (i = 0; i != 20; i = i + 1)   <---- It should be this!
    tt i_tt(.g (g), .o (array[i]));
endgenerate

endmodule
~~~~

tt.sv
~~~~
module tt
  (
  intf g,
  output logic [3:0] o
  );

assign o = 4'd7;

endmodule
~~~~


You can see that when I used a constant 20 (instead of "g.WIDTH") I get these additional lines in 

Vtop___024root__DepSet_heccd7ead__0__Slow.cpp

(I was diffing the generated files to find the differences in this test case, in one case with "i != 20" and the other with "i != g.WIDTH")

~~~~
39a40,49
>     vlSelf->top__DOT__i_t__DOT__i_u__DOT__array[0xaU] = 7U;
>     vlSelf->top__DOT__i_t__DOT__i_u__DOT__array[0xbU] = 7U;
>     vlSelf->top__DOT__i_t__DOT__i_u__DOT__array[0xcU] = 7U;
>     vlSelf->top__DOT__i_t__DOT__i_u__DOT__array[0xdU] = 7U;
>     vlSelf->top__DOT__i_t__DOT__i_u__DOT__array[0xeU] = 7U;
>     vlSelf->top__DOT__i_t__DOT__i_u__DOT__array[0xfU] = 7U;
>     vlSelf->top__DOT__i_t__DOT__i_u__DOT__array[0x10U] = 7U;
>     vlSelf->top__DOT__i_t__DOT__i_u__DOT__array[0x11U] = 7U;
>     vlSelf->top__DOT__i_t__DOT__i_u__DOT__array[0x12U] = 7U;
>     vlSelf->top__DOT__i_t__DOT__i_u__DOT__array[0x13U] = 7U;
~~~~

I can see that the array sized with "g.WIDTH" has the right size:

Vtop___024root.h:  
~~~~
  VlUnpacked<CData/*3:0*/, 21> top__DOT__i_t__DOT__i_u__DOT__array;
~~~~
